2 Holochain is an offshoot of Ceptr developed by The MetaCurrency Project. Instead of being coin based as blockchain systems like BitCoin are, it is user based. It uses a distributed hash table and fellow users, instead of miners, to organize and verify the authenticity of transactions, a 'do it yourself' alternative to mining for authenticity verification. One advantage of the HoloChain is that it requires much less memory than a BlockChain app, and thus can be run on hand held devices. As of early October 2017 the code for currency apps is being completed and verified. The HoloChain is also useful for distributed collaborative communication, and confirmation of reputation, among other things.

3 The bail-in policy was developed by a committee of the Bank for International Settlements, and ratified by the G20 countries in 2011.  This policy is based on the fact that money deposited in a bank becomes the property of the bank, as an unsecured loan from you or me.  To top it off, based on the Bankruptcy Reform Act of 2005, [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/ellen-brown/bailout-is-out-bailin-is-_b_3178702.html derivatives counter-parties are given preference] over all other creditors and customers of the bankrupt financial institution, including FDIC insured  depositors.  The great majority of derivatives counter-parties are the too big to fail banks themselves.

4 The argument is that in order for a long term investment to keep up with compound interest in value, it has to provide a greater income every year. If it has the same return every year, it is in effect a greater loss every year after the the first compared with the compound interest rate. So an investment becomes discounted, in other words is worth less than what compound interest will produce. The longer the payback on an investment, the greater the loss. So the more often you change investments and start the clock rolling again, the closer to compound interest will be your income. Thus compound interest leads investors to short term thinking.

5 Demurrage money has a charge placed against its balance on a regular basis. This charge is an agreed upon percentage of the balance. It has at least two purposes, funding system operation and promotion, and reinforcing long term thinking.

